# Purpose

Enforce security standards around authentication, JWT handling, cookies, secrets, and API access controls.

# Rules

## Authentication

-   Passwords MUST be hashed with `bcrypt` (10 rounds) before storage. DO NOT store plain-text passwords.
-   DO NOT log passwords, tokens, or secrets at any log level.
-   DO NOT return password hashes in API responses.

## JWT

-   Access tokens are short-lived and sent in the `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header.
-   Refresh tokens MUST be sent as `httpOnly` cookies ONLY. DO NOT expose them in response bodies.
-   DO NOT store JWT secrets in source code. They MUST come from environment variables (`config.accessTokenSecret`, `config.refreshTokenSecret`).
-   Validate JWT payload structure with Zod (`jwtPayloadSchema`) after `verify()`. DO NOT trust the decoded payload shape.

## Cookies

-   Refresh token cookie MUST be `httpOnly: true`, `secure: true` in production, `sameSite: 'strict'`.
-   DO NOT set cookies from frontend code for authentication.

## Authorization

-   All protected routes MUST use `authenticateContextMiddleware` to populate `req.context.user`.
-   DO NOT bypass authentication middleware in production routes.
-   Controllers MUST scope DB queries by `req.context.user.id`. DO NOT allow cross-user data access.

## Rate Limiting

-   Login, register, and refresh routes have per-route rate limiters (`loginLimiter`, `registerLimiter`, `refreshLimiter`).
-   DO NOT remove rate limiters from auth routes.

## Secrets and Environment Variables

-   DO NOT commit `.env`, `.env.dev`, `.env.production`, or `.env.integration.test` files.
-   Secrets are injected via Docker `env_file` directives or CI environment variables.
-   Config values are validated at startup via Zod schemas in `config/schemas/`.

## MongoDB

-   User email field is uniquely indexed. Duplicate key errors (code 11000) are caught by `exceptionsMiddleware` and surfaced as `ConflictException`.
-   DO NOT execute raw MongoDB queries with user-supplied filter values without type-safe mapping.

# Anti-Patterns

-   DO NOT disable `authenticateContextMiddleware` on routes that access user data.
-   DO NOT use `jwt.decode()` without `jwt.verify()` for authorization decisions.
-   DO NOT return stack traces in production error responses (`config.isDeveloping` gates this).
-   DO NOT store access tokens in `localStorage`; use Zustand in-memory store only.

# Checklist

-   [ ] Passwords hashed with bcrypt (10 rounds)
-   [ ] Refresh token in httpOnly cookie only
-   [ ] JWT payload validated with `jwtPayloadSchema` after decode
-   [ ] Protected routes have `authenticateContextMiddleware`
-   [ ] Rate limiters present on auth routes
-   [ ] No secrets committed to version control
